        <h2>About the Chapter</h2>
        <p>
            <strong>"Tiger in the Zoo"</strong> is a thought-provoking poem by Leslie Norris. The poem describes the contrasting lives of a tiger in the wild and a tiger in captivity. In its natural habitat, the tiger moves freely, stalking prey and living with dignity. However, in the zoo, the majestic animal is confined to a small cage, left to walk restlessly and helplessly.
        </p>
        <p>
            The poet uses powerful imagery and emotions to evoke sympathy for the caged tiger. The poem reminds us of the importance of freedom, the cruelty of captivity, and our responsibility towards animals. It raises awareness about animal rights and the unnatural life of wild creatures held in confinement for human amusement.
        </p>
        <p>
            Through this poem, Norris encourages readers to respect nature and animals, suggesting that all living beings deserve to live in their natural environment with freedom and respect.
        </p>
